{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525026"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:11:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:11:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14050"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14050"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.16,0.12,0.06,0.59]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6703"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55873"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6703"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14050"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41421"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"1419"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"3583"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13891"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44405"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55873"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of blurred vision, difficulty swallowing, and progressive muscle weakness. She reports eating home-canned vegetables three days ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. She has bilateral ptosis, diplopia, and symmetrical descending weakness of her limbs. Her sensation and mental status are intact. Reflexes are diminished throughout.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perform lumbar puncture","Administer intravenous immunoglobulin","Start high-dose corticosteroids","Initiate plasmapheresis","Administer botulinum antitoxin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patients symptoms are typical of a diagnosis of botulism, a syndrome caused by ingestion of the toxins from bacterium \u003Cem\u003EClostridium botulinum\u003C/em\u003E. The classic triad of botulism includes descending flaccid paralysis, intact sensation, and clear mental status, all of which are present in this case. The history of consuming home-canned vegetables is a significant risk factor, as improperly canned foods can harbor \u003Cem\u003EC. botulinum\u003C/em\u003E spores.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadminister botulinum antitoxin\u003C/strong\u003E. Early administration of antitoxin is crucial in preventing the progression of symptoms and reducing the duration of illness. The antitoxin binds to circulating botulinum toxin in the bloodstream, preventing it from attaching to nerve endings and causing further damage. It\u0027s important to note that antitoxin does not reverse existing paralysis but can prevent worsening of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG)\u003C/strong\u003E is not the treatment of choice for botulism. While IVIG is used in various neurological conditions, it is not effective against botulinum toxin and would not address the underlying cause of this patient\u0027s symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPerforming a \u003Cstrong\u003Elumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E is not immediately necessary in this case. Cerebrospinal fluid analysis is typically normal in botulism and would not contribute significantly to the diagnosis or management at this stage. The clinical presentation and history are often sufficient to make a presumptive diagnosis and initiate treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-dose corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated in the treatment of botulism. Steroids are often used in inflammatory or autoimmune neurological conditions, but botulism is caused by a toxin, not an inflammatory process. Corticosteroids would not address the underlying mechanism of nerve damage in botulism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasmapheresis\u003C/strong\u003E is not the standard treatment for botulism. While plasmapheresis can be useful in removing circulating antibodies or immune complexes in certain neurological conditions, it is not effective in removing botulinum toxin, which is primarily bound to nerve endings rather than circulating freely in the plasma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to antitoxin administration, supportive care is crucial in managing botulism. This may include mechanical ventilation if respiratory muscles are affected, nutritional support, and close monitoring in an intensive care setting. Proper diagnosis and prompt treatment are essential in improving outcomes for patients with botulism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Botulism is characterized by descending flaccid paralysis with intact sensation and mental status.","Botulinum toxin inhibits acetylcholine release at neuromuscular junctions, causing muscle weakness.","Early administration of antitoxin is crucial in treating botulism to prevent progression of symptoms."],"references":["Rao AK, Sobel J, Chatham-Stephens K, Luquez C. Clinical Guidelines for Diagnosis and Treatment of Botulism, 2021. MMWR Recomm Rep. 2021 May 7;70(2):1-30. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8112830/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41421"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14050"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41421"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T12:47:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T13:02:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6703"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55873"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data"